@node "mapedit_general" "MapEdit: generalities"

 As its name says, this software is an editor for maps, specialized to ease
 games development.
 
 Works with GIF or PNG files as tiles containor and tiles importation. 
 
 Use GIF for 2/16/256c games. GIF89a transparency is handled. No mandatory
 screenmode for GIF maps.
 
 Use PNG for high/true colors games. Transparency is handled for PNG only
 if Alpha channel is strict 0. You must have at least HC15 screenmode 
 to display of PNG maps.
    
 Requirements:
    
 ú EdDI cookie is mandatory, for offscreen VDI. Better choice is NVDI.
   
   NB: fVDI offscreen functions may seem available, but are not implemented.
   So alert is bypassed but GIF rasters won't be displayed. If you use fVDI
   as basic VDI layer, add also NVDI ontop to complete offscreen functions.
  
 ú Multitasking OS, NVDI and very quick CPU are strongly advised.
   
 ú GIFdec.ldg and GIFenc.ldg must be installed (LDG libraries) 
   to load and save GIF files.
   
 ú PNGdec.ldg and PNGenc.ldg must be installed (LDG libraries) 
   to load and save PNG files.
    
 ú the more RAM available, the merrier. Tiles number is limited to 32000.
   If you are short in RAM, then work in the lower-colors screenmode
   corresponding to the number of colors of your images.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_legal" "MapEdit: legal"

 MapEdit is freeware. Source code is provided for general knowledge,
 possible fork and issues search. Monetizing on this work is forbidden.
    
 It is strongly advised to make frequent backups of your datas.

 As always, we deny any responsibility concerning any errors, bugs
 or limitations of the program on your personal data, and on
 your computer. We try hard to seek out errors and to correct them.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_file_functions" "MapEdit: file functions"

 @{0U}Map folder structure@{0}

 With fileselector, find the map.inf file, it must be located in a folder
 named with ".map" extension.
 
 MapEdit reuses the MakeMAP (GIF/PNG slicer) tool output structure.

-> {foldername}.map\
-> {foldername}.map\map.inf (text file, descriptions)
-> {foldername}.map\map.dat (the tiles IDs 2D arrays values main raw table)
-> {foldername}.map\hnd.dat (hindrance optional array for the map)
-> {foldername}.map\nodes.csv    (nodes database for the map)
-> {foldername}.map\sublayer.vdi (optional sublayer ghosted image guide)
-> {foldername}.map\tplNNNNN.dat (the 2D arrays values templates raw tables)
-> {foldername}.map\hndNNNNN.dat (hindrance optional array for the templates)
-> {foldername}.map\nodNNNNN.csv (nodes database for the templates)
-> {foldername}.map\subNNNNN.vdi (optional sublayer for the templates)
 
-> {foldername}.map\tiles.gif|png (containor for tiles, preferred)
 or
-> {foldername}.map\tiles.set\ (contains each tiles files)

-> {foldername}.map\tiles.pxy (tiles optimization: offsets and effective areas)
 
 
 You may want to fork or use the tiles asset for other map, consider make
 a copy of the folder with its contents.
 
 Caution here with map width and height and values size: the map.dat depends
 on it.
 The map.dat file is raw 2D Byte|Word|Long array containing the tiles IDs.
 There is no header, so you can use it directly in your project as binary 
 include (or use my HexEdit to convert it to ASM/C includes).
 
 @{0B}Tip:@{0} The .dat files (map and templates) can be located outside 
 the .map folder, edit manualy the map.inf in the map folder and use complete
 pathnames (gemdos scripture with antislashes) pointing to the .dat files
 located in your gamedev project folder. 
 Just use other names than map.dat / hnd.dat / tplNNNNN.dat / hndNNNNN.dat.
 If they have these names, the files will be relocated at next save in
 the .map folder.

 You can also relocate the tiles.gif|png file elsewhere.
 

 @{0U}Drag'n'Drop from the desktop@{0}
 
 ARGV and Drag'n'Drop are supported to load maps: use the parent folder .map
 or the {foldername}.map\map.inf 
 
 If you drag'n'drop a GIF file on the GIF map, or PNG file on the PNG map,
 it will be imported as new tile on the current edited map.


 @{0U}Tiles storage@{0}

 For compatibility with old MakeMAP 1.0, the tiles.set folder is imported 
 and converted to {foldername}.map\tiles.gif|png
 
 A single GIF containor for whole tiles is more convenient: one General Color
 Table, and N frames for N tiles in this file. That ease disk access and
 space. Same for PNG, which handles APNG specifications, meaning several
 frames rasters can be stored in one file.


 @{0U}Tiles export (Edit menu, ^T)@{0}:
 
 If you want retreive tiles singletons files to convert these files to your
 own file format or package, there is 'Tiles export...' in the menu.
 Exported tile file name is tile ID, padded with left 0 to fit for 
 6 character width, with GIF or PNG extension. If a mask is detected, an 
 additionnal file can be generated (if Export Preference is checked), 
 with "m" tag present between ID and extension.
 
 The exported tiles must be located in a folder different from
 {foldername}.map.
 
 In the Export Preferences: you can crop each tile accordinly to the left and
 top offsets and displayable width and height (set in the tile infos).
 IDs, left and top offsets in the map grid and efficient width and height
 are exported to offsets.txt text tile beside the GIF|PNG files, in the same
 folder.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_tiles_list" "MapEdit: tiles list (F3)"

 View as @{0B}list@{0} or with a @{0B}grid@{0} (see Tiles list Preferences).

 - Tiles IDs correspond to the position in the list.
   
   Void tile is always 0, at top of the list. It is not exported or imported.
   Consider it implicit.
   
   Each tile have its own width and height, which are kept for map building
   and export. 
   
   Specific behavior for GIF format: GIF89a transparency is detected and
   handled for map display. The map color palette is read from tile ID=1.
    
   The tiles asset can be exported to singleton GIF or PNG images.
   Select a target folder. Tile file name is tile ID, padded with left 0 to
   fit for 6 character width, with GIF or PNG extension. 
   If a mask is generated,then "m" is present between ID and extension.

 - If the lock on tiles list is enabled, adding, removing and changing order
   button are hidden.
   
   If the lock is disabled, then the following features are allowed:

 - @{0B}Adding@{0}: new tile is imported from GIF or PNG file and added at
   the list bottom/end. 
 
 - @{0B}Removing@{0}: deleted tile will be replaced by the previous file or
   void (set this choice in the preferences). Automatic remap is done, that
   may take some time if the tile was at the debut.
   
   Tool to @{0B}clean tiles list@{0} (^K or Menu > Edit): removes all unused
   tiles in the map. Carefull if you use common tilesets.
   
 - @{0B}Reordering to previous or next@{0}: remap is also automatic but
   short. You may want to regroup same types of tiles (green, soil, walls,
   etc). List display is here more convenient than the grid.
   
   Remember position in the list = ID. If you want a common tiles asset for
   separated maps, consider using templates.

 - @{0B}Inspecting@{0}: opens tile informations, where offsets and surface
   can be changed manually.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_tile_infos" "MapEdit: tile infos (F4)"

 Basic informations: ID and physical width and height (stored in the tileset)
 
 Tile singleton is shown with red boundaries. Inside is the displayed area of
 the file.
 
 Here offsets and efficient surface can be manually set or changed. 
 If the changes are commited, the whole map and tiles list/grid are updated.
 
 This offsets and significant area is for optimization, to discard dead zones,
 speed up display and spare memory use in the game project.
 
 This informations are stored in tiles.pxy text file, generated automaticaly
 by MAKE_MAP tool, and can be reused into the game project.
 
 
 NB: the Detect function is based:
 - for GIF, on the transparency index else the background index of the file.
 - for PNG, on the same ARGB pixels in 2 or more corners of the tile.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_map_settings" "MapEdit: map settings (F2)"

 The map settings are divided in several panels.
 
 @{0U}General@{0}

   Here you can change the name and the size of the map.

   Buttons are there to commit changes or reset the size to the current one.
 
   Map width and height are limited to 32000, but that would handle a huge
   thing. Caution here, consider allocated memory and target for your game
   project.

 
 @{0U}Internals@{0} (templates will use the parent map internals settings)
 
 ú Tiles width and height are used here for horizontal and vertical padding.
   Each tile in the tileset can have its own width and height.
 
 ú About the map values size: maximum ID of tile is 32000.
   Byte storage allows 0 to 255 IDs, so 254 tiles + one void. This setting
   uses minimum memory but may be short for tiles variety.
   Word storage may be the most used.
   Long is proposed if you want to store something in the high-word.

 ú Lock on tiles list: if enabled then the tiles list window toolbar will be
   disabled and hidden. 
   Adding, removing, changing order of the tiles are no more allowed.
   
   This to keep tiles IDs constant for the current map and possibly others
   that may use the same tiles asset.

 
 @{0U}Hindrance@{0} (templates will the use parent map hindrance settings)
 
   You may choose to use tiles IDs to know/encode the hindrance and other
   tiles behaviors/qualities
   or
   you can enable this optional and additional array that will be separated
   and independant from the map contents array.
    
   This feature is intended for hindrance for sprites moves, but you can use
   this array for other purposes such as: 
   - slower or quicker moves on tile,
   - set positions for triggers or teleporters,
   - set enemy starting positions,
   - etc. 

 ú Enable or disable hindrance. The toolbar of the map contents windows will
   be expanded to add hindrance values on the map.
    
 ú Values can be boolean or byte encoded. The array is saved in hnd*.dat
   raw file, respectively a bitfield or bytes suite. Use map general width
   and height to point to correct value.
    
   - Boolean: 0 for void = move is allowed    
              1 for crossed bar = move is not permitted on this tile
               
   - Byte: 0 for void = move is allowed, nothing special
           1 for filled bar = move may not be permitted on this tile
           2 to 255 values are your choice of meaning
           
   You can swap between boolean and byte use while editing the map, but you
   may loose information if you save the map with boolean choice.
            
 ú If Byte encoding is used, you can assign values to predefined shapes.
   These assignments are stored in the map.inf file.
  
   Shapes are proposed if you want to manage fine hindrance on tiles, where 
   the void part is still allowed for moves.
   Or other custom shapes can symbolize other behavior or position.
  
   These shapes are stored in MAPEDIT.RSC file (tree 14), 16x16px G_IMAGE.
   You can tell me what shapes you want to add, or you can add some
   yourself, up to 256 shapes (and RSC file size).
    
   NVDI is highly advised for its bitmap scaling features: if the tile width
   and height (set in the Internals panel) are not 16x16px, then the shape
   will be drawn reduced or expanded to the tile padding.     

   The hindrance value is displayed if not assigned to a shape.
   
 
 @{0U}Colors@{0} (templates will use the parent map colors settings)
   
 ú Here is display choosen the file format for the tiles. 
   GIF for 2/16/256c maps or PNG for true color maps.
   Choice is made in a GEM alert when creating a new map, choice can still
   be modified if the tileset has only void ID 0 tile, but once the first
   tile ID 1 is imported, then the file format is locked.
    
   You may later hack and replace tileset GIF <> PNG by editing the
   .map/map.inf file. There is a flag named TILES_PNG_FORMAT to set to
   TRUE or FALSE. Be careful at the consistency.
   
 
 @{0U}Tools@{0}
   
 ú Translate contents up/left/right/down: shift whole map to the direction.
 
 ú Lock to avoid tile|template|hindrance drawing, protecting the gridded datas.
   This may help avoiding interferences when you put nodes on the map.

 ú Add template: instead of mouse-select with Shift key held, you can add a
   new empty template or duplicate current map or template (with tilemap and
   hindrance, without nodes).


 @{0U}Sublayer@{0} (only for HC15 to TC32 videomodes display)

 ú You may need help drawing tiles according to a canvas/model (ie original
   game map). This feature allows to display in the background an image, loaded
   from a PNG for GIF formated file. Use the Add button or drag'n'drop the 
   image file onto this subpanel.
   
   Default option is to make this image brighter, seen as ghost to discriminate
   from the tiles you draw. This filtering takes time for PNG format at 
   sublayer generation, so be carefull with large images.
   
   The sublayer is stored as VDI file (20 bytes MFDB + raster datas) in the
   .MAP folder and is bitplane-number dependant ie you'll have to reload the
   sublayer if your working setup has the videomode changed.
   This file is not compressed to speed up reloads and may be huge: 
   careful if your setup is short of RAM and disk.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_map_contents" "MapEdit: map contents (F1)"

 Maps can be sorted with  and  buttons. For now, it will have only effects
 in the pop-up selector. It's planned for background/top to foreground/bottom
 future maps displayed as multiple layers.
 
 Tip: the turning icon right in the pop-up selects next map or template. Use
      Shift key with mouse click on this icon to select previous one.
 
 Several coordinates are displayed for information when the mouse cursor is
 on the map area of the window.
 
 Transparency display may require full white for VDI index 0 color.
 
 The toolbar can be in 2 modes:
 
 ú reduced: no template available, no hindrance enabled, 
            only @{"tile" LINK "mapedit_tiles"} drawing is possible.
            
 ú expanded: when a template is available and/or hindrance is enabled.
  
    Here choose the drawing mode: @{"tile" LINK "mapedit_tiles"} or @{"template" LINK "mapedit_templates"} or @{"hindrance" LINK "mapedit_hindrance"}.
    The selected tile is choosen in the tiles window.
    The selected template and hindrance are choosen in the pop-up lists.
  
@endnode

@node "mapedit_tiles" "MapEdit: map contents, working with tiles"
 
 @{0B}Left mouse click@{0} puts in the map contents the selected tile 
 from the tile list/grid.
 
 @{0B}Right mouse click@{0} selects in the list the tile under the mouse
 cursor position in the map contents. 
 This to ease tile selection from map for drawing comfort.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_templates" "MapEdit: map contents, working with templates"

 A template can be considered as 
 - a group of tiles, so draw easily with tiles blocks.
 or 
 - a sub-map, that can be used as scenes or small screens.
 
 A map can own several templates.
 
 Templates are saved within the .map folder, and use the map common tileset.
 Their internals settings are the map's internals.  
 Their name and size (general settings) can be modified and are stored in
 the map.inf file. 
 Their sub-map 2D values are stored in specific tplNNNNN.dat raw files.
 
 @{0B}To create@{0} a template, select an area from the current map by
 pressing a Shift key, then holding the left mouse button and moving the
 cursor. A rubberbox is shown to show more or less the area to grab/select. 
 The template is created after the left mouse button is released.
 
 @{0B}To remove@{0} a template, select it from the map pop-up selector then
 use the Close option in the menu (shortcut: ^Del).
 
 @{0B}Usage:@{0}
 
 If a template exists for a map, the map contents toolbar is expanded and
 choice is proposed to use either a selected tile to draw or a template
 to paste.
 
 You can draw tiles in templates.
 You can paste a template within the map or another template.
 
 NB: when you draw a template, it's just a group of tiles that are put onto the
 map or another template. If you modify the template, already drawn templates
 won't be modified ie there is no link.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_hindrance" "MapEdit: map contents, working with hindrance"
 
 A small "hindrance" button is there to show and hide the hindrance 
 array in the map display.
 
 @{0B}Left mouse click@{0} puts in the map contents the selected hindrance.
 
 @{0B}Right mouse click@{0} selects in the pop-up list the hindrance value
 under the mouse cursor position in the map contents.
 This to ease hindrance selection from map for drawing comfort.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_nodes" "MapEdit: working with nodes (F5 & F6)"

 Nodes are points located on maps and templates. To create one,
 use "+" button for path|trigger pop-up on the nodes list, then pick a pixel
 on the selected map or template.
 
 The nodes list toolbar helps manage and sort nodes. The nodes datas are stored
 in *.CSV text tiles in the .MAP folder. Unlike binary tiled and hindrance 
 2D arrays that can be relocated outside the .MAP folder to be used directly
 in the developped game, node datas *.CSV files remain in the .MAP folder
 because exportation is required to mine/exploit these infos (see Edit menu).
 
 Node name, location, type and links|values are edited in the node infos panel.
 Tricks:
 - use Shift with click on the arrows buttons for a 10px move instead of 1px.
 - last seen trigger values are proposed for a new trigger-node.
 
 A node can be of 3 types:
 
 ú for paths, a starting node can be linked to 8 others ending nodes
   (thinking of the eight directions on a joystick). If valid, the link is
   drawn on the map or template to set path/lined-trajectory or
   pixeled hindrance (ground, oblique ground, etc).
 
   Exportation to path generate series of groups of x,y points that can be
   considered as each pixels of the drawn line in @{"*.PTH" LINK "mapedit_file_pth"} file.
 
 ú for triggers, a node can store 8 values (0 to 32000) of your choice, that
   can be IDs, types, sub-types, maximums, variables, etc.
 
   Exportation to binary @{"*.TRG" LINK "mapedit_file_trg"} file.
   
 ú for ungridded tiles, see @{"description" LINK "mapedit_file_tlt"} and file format.
   
 
 A copy/paste system helps creating nodes:
 - ^C and ^V when the nodes list window is on top.
 - Copy button at bottom of the node infos window to copy current node.
 - Paste as new in the pop-up adding button in the nodes list window.
 
 Informations will be copied/pasted with a shift in x/y coordinates (its value
 can be changed in the @{"preferences" LINK "mapedit_prefs_nodes"}), except links if node is for paths.
 You can copy from a map or template and paste to same map and templates
 childs (ie same tileset).
 
 ^Left and ^Right on already selected node selects previous or next node.
 ^A selects all in the nodes list window.
 
 
 Tip: for grouped nodes move, in the nodes list window, select multiple nodes
 using using Shift key and mouse click, then open the '?' pop-up and use the
 arrows to change coordinates of all selected nodes. Same as in the node infos
 windows, using Shift and click on arrow translates with a bigger shift than 1
 pixel (its value can be changed in the @{"preferences" LINK "mapedit_prefs_nodes"}).
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_file_pth" "MapEdit: PTH file format"
 
 Binary file containing a long suite of int16_t values, that can be grouped
 as segments (ie lines in the map) of variable lengths.
 
 segment
 {
   int16_t node_id; // start of the link
   int16_t node_id; // end of the link
   int16_t points_number; // 0 < N <= 32000
   int16_t x1; // x of the starting point
   int16_t y1; // y of the starting point
   int16_t x2;
   int16_t y2;
   ...
   int16_t xN; // x of the ending point
   int16_t yN; // y of the ending point
 }
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_file_trg" "MapEdit: TRG file format"
 
 Binary file, containing a suite of trigger-type nodes structures, sorted like
 in the nodes list.
 
 struct 
 {
   int16_t node_id;
   int16_t x;
   int16_t y;  
   int16_t value1;  
   int16_t value2;  
   int16_t value3;  
   int16_t value4;  
   int16_t value5;  
   int16_t value6; 
   int16_t value7;  
   int16_t value8; 
 }
 
 Size is always a 22 bytes multiple.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_file_tlt" "MapEdit: ungridded tiles list"
 
 Some elements (tiles or sprites) of scenery may be not located in the
 2D array grid, but at pixelized position, with x,y coordinates. 
 Using nodes with ungridded tiles type will help here to compose complex 
 sceneries with a group of tiles or sprites (masks are handled).
 
 Display order in the map contents:
 - regular gridded tiles, accordingly to the 2D array.
 - ungridded tiles, sorted as in the nodes list.
 - paths (+ and links) and triggers (*) and hidden ungridded tiles (#).
 
 Indicate the tile ID and commit with the Change button, or drag'n'drop
 a tile ontop the node infos window from the tiles list.
 
 The display flag for each ungridded tile allows to evaluate locations. 
 Using a @{"sublayer" LINK "mapedit_map_settings"} may help reconstitute game screens.
 
 You may need also some static coordinates for sprites, here use tile ID 0
 for objects that don't below to the tiles list.
 
 The *.TLT file is a binary file containing a list for ungridded tiles, *
 sorted like in the nodes list.
 
 struct 
 {
   int16_t node_id;
   int16_t x;
   int16_t y;  
   int16_t tile_id;  
   int16_t bitfield; // for now, only bit 0 is used for display on/off
 }
 
 Size is always a 10 bytes multiple.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_paths" "MapEdit: preferences: paths"
 
 ú Magnifier helper: path of the magnify tool (use AES_LUPE.APP or other).
                     call it from the Options menu or F10 key.
 
 ú Maps folder: new maps are stored preferentialy here
 
 ú Logfile: on FreeMiNT, enabled by default on u:\ram\mapedit.log
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_tiles_font" "MapEdit: preferences: font"
 
 ú Choose a convenient font and its size for the displayed lists.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_tiles_list" "MapEdit: preferences: tiles list"
 
 ú Display can be as grid (bubbles used for infos) instead of list and text.

 ú Map contents and tiles list windows can be linked for comfort.
 
 ú In case of tile removal from the list, select the replacement tile:
   either the previous one in the list, either void tile (ID 0).
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_map_settings" "MapEdit: preferences: map settings"
 
 ú Allow lowercases for files names: enabled by default on FreeMiNT
                                     if not, uppercases are used
 
 ú Opens automatically for new maps: to modify defaults values at start.
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_map_contents" "MapEdit: preferences: map contents"
 
 ú Void pattern and color: to show void tiles and transparency.
 
 ú Show borders or not, with choosen color, in case of map is smaller than
   window size.
   
 ú Hindrance optional array, with choosen color and the writing mode:
  - replace: black pixels are written on the whole tile.
  - transparent: only colored pixels are drawn, black pixels are omitted.
  - XOR: colored pixels are mixed with the tile pixels. 

 ú Nodes, with choosen color and the writing mode:
  - replace or transparent (no difference, since it's drawn with VDI primitive.
  - XOR: colored pixels are mixed with the tile pixels. 
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_export" "MapEdit: preferences: export"
 
 For tiles:
 
 ú Generate masks images files, GIF or PNG, if transparency is detected during
   tiles export.
 
 ú Use offsets and crop when exporting tiles, accordingly to the displayable
   offsets and surface (see @{"tile infos" LINK "mapedit_tile_infos"}).
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_prefs_nodes" "MapEdit: preferences: nodes"
 
 ú When pasting nodes with ^V key or 'Paste as new' pop-up item, you can
   customize the X and Y shift on pasted nodes from the original copied nodes.
   0 is default (= same coordinates). Can be from -256 px to 256 pixels.
   
 ú Add or not " (copy)" label to the pasted node name.
 
 ú When moving a node in the node infos window, or using the arrows if the '?'
   pop-up (grouped translation), and using the Shift key, you can customize
   the pixels shift.
   Not using the Shift key, pixel shift is always 1 px.
   Using the Shift key, pixels shift can be from 2 px to 64 px. 
 
@endnode

@node "mapedit_history" "MapEdit: history"

 @{0B}1.6E@{0}
 - add: removed tile ID is indicated in mapedit.log for "Clean tiles list".
 - fix: cleaning tile list was effective only for map, not related templates.
 - mod: node(s) deletion is moved from nodes list toolbar to action pop-up.
 - fix: double-click on nodes list first item didn't open node infos.
 - fix: could not paste nodes from template to parent map.
 - fix: avoid tiles list rebuild if same tileset (no redraws needed when 
        browsing within parent map and its templates).
 - fix: large tiles display in tiles list when view is not grid.
 - fix: goto tiles list bottom after tiles were added.
 - fix: map modified flag wasn't set when deleting, pasting, reordering nodes.

 @{0B}1.6D@{0}
 - add: Preferences > Nodes: when pasting, customize x and y pixels shift
        (0 is default, from -256 to 256 px).
 - add: Preferences > Nodes: when pasting, flag to add " (copy)" to the node
        name or not.
 - add: Preferences > Nodes: customize move shift when using Shift key
        (10 is defautl, from 2 to 64 px). 
 - add: in nodes list, "?" is now pop-up where you can move nodes selection
        (purpose is for group move by multiple selection).
 - add: pop-up with slider: use Shift key on turning icon to select previous
        item (without click, select next item).

 @{0B}1.6C@{0}
 - fix: loading GIF tileset forgot transparency informations.
 - fix: update ungridded tiles-nodes index when reordering or removing
        items in the tileset.
 - fix: could not paste text (^V with scrap.txt) in nodes infos window.
 - fix: extends nodes copy/paste for multiple selection. 
        When pasting, x,y-shift is now 16px (previously 4px). 
 - fix: extends nodes copy/paste to map and templates childs on same tileset
        (previously only for current map or template).
 - add: menu Options > Open map folder entry (or F8 key).
 - add: F9 key shortcut to open MapEdit tools folder.
 - add: set void pattern and color also in node infos window.
 - fix: when adding tiles by drag'n'droping folders from desktop: sort by
        filenames for better ordering.
 - fix: map settings: didn't display tools > draw lock flag accordingly to
        internal flags.
 - fix: deleting or reordering nodes didn't update map contents window.
 - fix: cleaning tiles list function forgot to count tiles used by nodes.
 - fix: redraw at nodes list when scrolling to bottom (bad index).
 - fix: creates new ungridded tile-node preferably with selected tile from
        the tiles list.
 - fix: Export > Tiles list... menu item wasn't working.

 @{0B}1.6B@{0}
 - add: in map settings > tools: add template with New and Duplicate buttons.
 - add: copy/paste system for nodes (^C and ^V in node list window, Paste as
        new in pop-up, Copy button in node infos).
 - add:  and  buttons, ^Left and ^Right in nodes windows for quick node
        selection.
 - add: indicates GIF transparent color index if present in tile infos window.
 - fix: bad indexes when modifying RSC objects states (= bad pokes). 
 - fix: on tiles masks and surfaces displayed for ungridded tiles nodes.
 - fix: forgot to save drawing lock state for templates in the .map datafiles.
 - fix: adding tiles was effective only if map was selected, not on a template.
 - fix: ^I on nodes list window opens node infos instead of map settings.
 - fix: in map contents, could not select map/template if pop-up item > 20. 
 - fix: save only modified or new sublayers, delete .vdi files if removed.
 - fix: was loading nodNNNNN.csv only if map' nodes.csv existed.
 - fix: was not using parent's map tileset for nodes in templates.
 - fix: could add sublayer by drag'n'drop evenif disabled.

 @{0B}1.6@{0}
 - add: sublayer as brighter background image guide. 
        Add GIF or PNG in the map settings. Only for HC15 to TC32 videomodes.
 - add: new node type for ungridded tile (precise position, out of the grid,
        sorted and displayed by the node list).
 - add: nodes locations x,y and some values can now be negative 
        (range -32000 to +32000).
 - add: map settings: drawing with mouse cursor can be locked (security to
        avoid interferences with locating ungridded tiles).
 - fix: nodes list file too slow to load.
 - fix: 'Close' menu function did not clean correctly tiles nor its templates. 
 - fix: 'Close' menu function could freeze the maps pop-up selector.
 - fix: glitches around surface-optimized tiles on map tile-per-tile scrolling.
 - fix: transparency detection for GIF when adding a tile in tiles list.
 - fix: transparency display in tile infos.
 - fix: alert and abort if loading map with PNG tiles if videomode < HC15.
 - fix: on BMOVE with extra large sizes.
 - fix: unwanted cursor redraws in edit fields.

 @{0B}1.5@{0}
 - add: nodes on maps and templates, that can be of 2 types:
        - for paths, a node can be linked to 8 others nodes, exportation
          to path generate series/segments of x,y points in *.PTH file.
        - for triggers, a node can store 8 values (0 to 32000), exportation
          to binary *.TRG file. New trigger-type node have the values of the
          previous edited trigger-type node.
        See in this guide, the formats of the *.PTH and *.TRG files.
 - fix: could not load templates (conflict with tiles.pxy file).
 - fix: 'Save as...' opens was opening inside the current .map folder
        instead of parent folder.
 - add: menu entry to open desk window for MapEdit tools.
 - add: MakePoints app in tools (formerly "Moves" from Xenon II: Reloaded dev).
 - mod: map contents borders Preferences keys have changed, please reset that. 
 - mod: hindrance display flag in toolbar moved to Preferences panel.
 - mod: preferences in menu moved to Preferences panel.
 - add: some text bubbles
 - del: map timestamp removed.
 - fix: priority to use SHEL_FIND to locate the resource file.
 - fix: may not set preferences at start.
 - fix: didn't close PNG codec if asked by LDG manager.

 @{0B}1.4@{0}
 - add: tile infos (F4 or double-click on unselected tile in the list/grid). 
 - add: tiles optimization, using displayed left and top offsets and
        surface. This to speed up map display, and spare memory use in the
        final program. Dislayed area can be manually changed in the tile infos.
 - add: export masks for PNG (transparency if ARGB = 0RGB)
 - add: PNG transparency on map display (alpha channel must be 0).
 - fix: crash under MagiC (read integer at 0 address for PNG maps).
 - add: Edit menu option: export with or without masks.
 - add: Edit menu option: when exporting tiles from containor to singletons,
        can crop tiles according to the displayed offsets and surface.
        offsets.txt is added to the GIF|PNG tiles files, listing ID, left, top,
        width, height.
 - add: can call AES_LUPE.APP from MapEdit, from the menu or F5 key, 
        set its path in the preferences.
 - add: mouse cursor progress shape for tilesets containor load, save, export.
 - fix: save tileset only if necessary (could be long for PNG containors).

 @{0B}1.3@{0}
 - add: handles PNG image files for tiles (maps has only type: GIF or PNG).
 - add: handles BGEM.NG notifications (for preferences and gxalloc routines).
 - mod: changes for GIFdec.ldg and GIFenc.ldg modified API.
 - fix: finally stable under MagiC for GIFdec.ldg
 - fix: wrong map pointer (possible crash) when loading tiles.
 - fix: crash (visible on MagiC environment) just after loading map.
 - fix: undo/redo ineffective when reaching limits of the history.
 - add: can use Undo key (Atari behavior).
 - fix: adding a tile could have wrong ID if several maps are edited.
 - fix: GIF 16c (and maybe 256c) tiles had wrong colors indexes.
 - fix: recalculate grid view after adding new tile (tile max size may change).
 - fix: could not remove tile ID 1.
 - fix: missing bottom row & right column in the window map.
 - fix: could not change tile ID if tile was partly masked by window sliders.
 - fix: log disabled at start, was not read correctly from the preferences file.
 - fix: logfile name could be path only.
 - fix: tops window if click on text field and untopped window. 
 - fix: changed alert message, can't save automaticaly the converted
        \tiles.set\ folder into tiles.gif|png containor.
 
 See MAKE_MAP changes, with PNG support and pre-existing tileset at input.

 @{0B}1.2@{0}
 - add: hindrance optional and additional array, encoded as Boolean or Byte,
        saved in separated raw files, can assign some values to predefined 
        shapes. More details in the updated HYP guide.
 - fix: possible division by zero while obtaining coordinates.
 - fix: crash when cursor was on void tile while displaying coordinates.
 - fix: crash if drawing outside map area (small map/templates).
 - fix: creating new template from a template took map datas instead.
 - fix: avoid memory allocation for palette template (use palette of the map).
 - fix: menu save entry was disabled while template was modified.
 - chg: map "metadatas" renamed map "settings".

 @{0B}1.1@{0}
 - add: templates (= group of tiles = blocks = sub-maps) using the map tileset,
        press Shift key then select the area by holding the left mouse button
        and moving the cursor.
 - add: grid view for tiles list (^G), infos in bubble.
 - add: clean tiles list function,
        which removes all unused tiles in the map and templates.
 - mod: panels for settings window (Internals panel disabled for templates).
 - add: ARGV support (launch with several .map folders),
        code by Gregor Duchalski/GFA_BIND/PDATS627.
 - fix: in map part raster redraw (right and bottom of large maps). 
 - fix: "save as..." menu entry always disabled.
 - fix: tiles toolbar wasn't masked if tiles lock on.
 - fix: in retreiving fonts names.

 @{0B}1.0@{0}
 + first functional release
 + provided with MakeMAP (GIF slicer), moved from P2SM tools.
 + AES-Lupe util (from NVDI package) to better view tiles on large screens.
 
@endnode

